# Copy to `.env` for local development.
#
# --- HTTP / security (Express) ---
# Comma-separated browser origins allowed for credentialed CORS (e.g. https://pdfpilot.pro,http://localhost:5173).
# If unset, any Origin is accepted (fine for local dev; set in production on Render).
# ALLOWED_ORIGINS=https://pdfpilot.pro,http://localhost:5173
# Behind Render/nginx: trust first proxy hop for correct client IP (rate limits). Set TRUST_PROXY_HOPS=0 to disable.
# TRUST_PROXY_HOPS=1
# Production GET /health returns only { ok, service }. Set true for full binary paths + versions (ops debugging).
# HEALTH_VERBOSE=true
# Rate limits (per IP, sliding ~15 min window): optional overrides — defaults are safe for normal use.
# RATE_LIMIT_CPU_HEAVY_MAX=40
# RATE_LIMIT_UPLOAD_MAX=60
# RATE_LIMIT_EDIT_MAX=400
#
# Optional: separate Gotenberg service (e.g. docker-compose.document-flow.yml) — the pdfpilot **web app**
# no longer calls the API for Word→PDF (that route was removed). Keep Gotenberg only if you use it for
# other integrations.
# GOTENBERG_URL=http://localhost:3044
#
# Production on Render: the Blueprint no longer defines a Gotenberg service for pdfpilot (cost/clarity).
# Local compose below still works if you experiment with Gotenberg separately.
# GOTENBERG_HOSTPORT=some-service:12345
# Optional: LibreOffice headless — **PDF → Word** on the API (POST /document-flow/convert-pdf-to-docx
# and GET …/export-docx). Word → PDF in the SPA does **not** use the API.
# Also enables: PDF→Excel, PDF→PowerPoint, PPTX/XLSX/HTML→PDF (see POST /document-flow/convert-* routes).
# If SOFFICE_PATH is unset, the server tries `soffice` on PATH, then /usr/bin/soffice, /usr/local/bin/soffice,
# and the default macOS app bundle path below.
# macOS headless: pdfpilot does not force SAL_USE_VCLPLUGIN=svp (unstable with Aqua); it sets SAL_SKIA=raster
# and SAL_DISABLEGL=1 unless you override (e.g. SAL_DISABLEGL=0 SAL_SKIA=metal).
# SOFFICE_PATH=/usr/bin/soffice
# macOS:
# SOFFICE_PATH=/Applications/LibreOffice.app/Contents/MacOS/soffice
#
# PDF text translation (POST /document-flow/translate) — tries LibreTranslate first when an API key is set.
# If the public LibreTranslate host rejects the request (no key), the server falls back to MyMemory (free quota).
# LIBRETRANSLATE_URL=https://libretranslate.com
# LIBRETRANSLATE_API_KEY=
#
# --- OCR PDF (POST /ocr-pdf): ocrmypdf + Tesseract — installed in the production Docker image ---
# Optional override for the binary path (default: /usr/bin/ocrmypdf or PATH).
# OCRMYPDF_BIN=/usr/bin/ocrmypdf
# Max pages processed per request (longer PDFs are truncated before OCR). Default 40, max 100.
# OCR_MAX_PAGES=40
# Wall-clock timeout in ms (default 540000 = 9 minutes).
# OCR_TIMEOUT_MS=540000
# Tesseract language packs (default in code: eng). Docker image sets OCR_LANGS=eng+hin via Dockerfile ENV.
# OCR_LANGS=eng
#
# --- Edit PDF: download gate (Firebase Admin + optional first anonymous download) ---
# DOWNLOAD_AUTH_ENABLED=false
# When false, guests can still download without signing in, but signed-in users who send a Bearer
# token still hit the 3/day free limit (and Pro unlimited) as long as Firebase Admin + Firestore work.
# When true, GET /download requires a valid Firebase ID token OR a one-time downloadToken from POST /upload.
# FIREBASE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON={"type":"service_account",...}   # full JSON on one line (Render secret)
# Needed for GET /subscription/me, POST /user-sessions/register, etc. Without it those routes return 503 auth_unavailable (browser-only tools such as PDF→Word still work).
# Or: GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS=/absolute/path/to/serviceAccount.json
# Local dev: save the downloaded key as backend/firebase-service-account.local.json and set
# GOOGLE_APPLICATION_CREDENTIALS=./firebase-service-account.local.json (paths relative to backend/ are OK).
#
# First download without sign-in (server-issued token from /upload). Set false to require OAuth every time.
# DOWNLOAD_FIRST_ANONYMOUS=true
#
# --- My Documents (signed-in library): POST /user-sessions/register, GET /user-sessions/library, DELETE,
# POST /user-sessions/duplicate (copy session), PATCH /user-sessions/:sessionId (rename in library) … ---
# Uses the same Firebase Admin credentials as /download when verifying Bearer tokens.
# Registers uploads/{sessionId}/owner.json (7-day retention) and writes Firestore users/{uid}/documents/{sessionId}
# via the Admin SDK (no client-side Firestore rules required for the list).
# Enable Firestore (Native mode) on the same Firebase project as the service account.
#
# Frontend: see ../frontend/.env.example — copy to frontend/.env.development and set VITE_FIREBASE_* for log in / sign up UI.
# Optional: VITE_DOWNLOAD_AUTH_ENABLED=true  (mirrors UX expectations; server still enforces when DOWNLOAD_AUTH_ENABLED=true)
# Optional: deploy firestore.rules if the client ever writes to Firestore; library list uses the API + Admin only.
#
# --- Razorpay (Pro subscription) ---
# Keys from Razorpay Dashboard → API Keys. Webhook secret: Settings → Webhooks → your endpoint → signing secret.
# RAZORPAY_KEY_ID=rzp_live_xxxx
# RAZORPAY_KEY_SECRET=xxxx
# RAZORPAY_WEBHOOK_SECRET=xxxx
# After payment.captured, the API updates Firestore (same project as Firebase Admin). Webhook URL (production):
#   https://YOUR-API-HOST/subscription/webhooks/razorpay
# Optional: grace after `expiresAt` before treating a user as free again (ms). Default 172800000 (48h).
# SUBSCRIPTION_GRACE_MS=172800000
#
# --- Public feedback (home page) ---
# GET /feedback and POST /feedback store JSON in backend/data/site-feedback.json (gitignored). Ephemeral disk on
# serverless hosts may reset the file on redeploy — migrate to a database when you need durable archives.
#
# Optional admin (list all, add curated review, delete): set a long random secret, then:
#   curl -H "Authorization: Bearer YOUR_SECRET" https://api.example.com/feedback/admin
# Frontend (not linked in nav): /admin/feedback — paste the same secret once per browser session.
# FEEDBACK_ADMIN_SECRET=   # min 16 chars, e.g. openssl rand -hex 24
